column168: Driving east on Hwy 84 pass exit 103 by the town of Morgan Ut, driver was going around 50 mph driving on snow plowed lane, loss track going over a bridge with major pot holes. Steer into direction of median and then when into median, roll on passanger side, trailer then slided pulling the truck over to the driver side, a piece on ladder on trailer broke and poked 1 inch hole into truck tank. In the 2 compartment on the truck that had the hole, only 800 gallons was in the compartment. With the truck on it side, the hole was over half way up when no product being release. a 1500 About 100 gallons came out. DOT snow plow stop, called police. Floor dry was put on the frozen ground. Since it wasn't leaking no other steps where taken then. The cleanup company came with a vacuum truck to suck up the diesel on the ground.
column169: Better training, instead of once a year defense driving class possible having 2. In driving meeting on 2/13, go over accident with pictures and talk about what we could have done better. In bad weather conditions, drop second trailer and use just the lead trailer. Limit night driving to in town deliveries only. Know your drivers, what they can do and can't do. What experince they have with winter driving and what to look for on the road. Have DOT or Highway Patrol teach a class on winter driving.

column168: GATX 16375 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported emanating a chemical odor in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 16375. The responder noted that all seals were intact and the odor was emanating from the manway cover closure. Some dampness mixed with dried commodity residue was noted around the base of the manway nozzle. The responder found all six manway securement bolts less than tool tight (five approx. 1/2 turn loose and one at a full turn loose). Responder properly tool tightened these loose securement bolts, but the commodity odor persisted. Afterwards, GATX 16375 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection of the manway gasket seal and the cleaning of the spillage around the manway nozzle. At 0945 hrs. PST, 2/09/08, a shipper response team arrived and installed a new manway gasket after they discovered that the manway gasket was missing in GATX 16375. The gasket was applied and the manway resecured by 1030 hrs. PST, 2/09/08. Another shipper contractor neutralized the spillage on the shell on GATX 16375 which was completed by 1230 hrs. PST, 2/09/08. No spillage impacted the ground.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On February 2, 2008 at 02:57 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered TILX 110133, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid fuming from the top of the tank car. TILX 110133 was isolated and the shipper, Olin Corporation, NY-DEC and the NRC were notified. Miller Environmental Service, a CSXT response contractor, and a CSXT Sentinel were dispatched to the scene and found the PRD-Vent plug and rupture disc missing from the assembly. Contractor personnel secured the assembly and decontaminated the car. Olin Corporation sent representatives who installed a replacement assembly, the leak was secured and the car released for disposition. A special switch of TILX 110133 was made to the North Cleanout track for isolation  Cause Code:  420  NARRI:  2 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: While driving on Hemlock Rd to make a delivery, the driver began up the crest of a hill.  The road beyond the summit was covered in ice.  The driver slid on the ice and lost control of the vehicle.  He attempted to regain control of the truck by driving into a ditch on the right.  Once the front wheels made contact with the ditch, the rear end swung around on the ice turning the vehicle across the road and over an embankment.  The truck continued over the embankment, laying on its passenger side and sliding approximately 50-70 feet from the roadway.
column169: Advise all drivers of proper safty protocol and counter-measures.

column168: GLNX 34506 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found the thermometer well pipe cracked allowing product vapor to escape.  The contents of the car was transferred to another tank car for forwarding to destination.  Product vapors were flared to reduce the interior pressure to 0 psi.    The defective thermometer well pipe was removed and replaced with a plug stopping the release.  The car was moved to a tank car shop under FRA Movement Authority for further inspection and repairs.

column168: DUPX 12561 was noted by carrier personnel emitting a vapor from the top of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco Inc, along with personnel from the shipper's origin plant responded and found the tell-tale needle valve on the side of the pressure relief device partially open allowing an intermittent release of product vapor when the car was moved.    Release of vapor from this device indictates the frangible disc in the base of the combination PRD has ruptured.  Properly closing the tell-tale needle valve stopped the release.    The PRD will be removed and the frangible disc replaced after unloading.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: J.B. Hunt Transport was notified from the BNSF rail that there was material leaking from the container of this load.  We dispatched our maintenance crew to go to the scene of the incident to verify what type of material was leaking.  Without entering the container, our maintenance crew was able to determine that the leaking substance was paint from visual and from the fumes released from the container.  At that point, we dispatched a environmental crew for remediation of the container.  From photos as well as the reporting from the environmental crew, the cause of the spill was due to package failure of one of the pails.  It was damaged due to having too much weight put upon the packaging.  The environmental team took the necessary steps to properly clean up the spill and dispose of the product.
column169: Notification has been sent to the shipper of this cargo that a release had happened.  Complete information as to why the spill occurred will also be sent for documentation.  Recommendation for additional training and/or better blocking/bracing will be provided to the shipper.

column168: On February 15, 2007, personnel in the CSXT Rice yard in Waycross, GA observed WCHX 23122, a loaded tank car of cruse sulfate turpentine, dripping from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and the shipper notified. A CSXT environmental supervisor responded and found the bottom outlet cap less than tool tight and the bottom outlet valve handle not secured in the closed position, with no seal present. The valve was closed, the cap tightened, the leak stopped and the car was released for transportation. No special switching move was required.    NARRI = 5(5+1+ 0)(2+0) = 60  NARRI Code = 148
column169: No additional comments.

All bolts were properly secured stopping the release.

column168: 02/08/2008: Shipper advised us (the carrier) after we received their cargo (in a closed freight container) that the freight container actually contained hazmat (i.e. UN 3166, Vehicle, Flammable Liquid Powered). Upon discovery, we (the carrier) placed this shipment on hold pending proper shipping papers and placarding and/or marks. Subsequently, the vehicle "warning" mark was applied to the subject container and an appropriate dangerous goods declaration was received. Shipment was released from hold by us (the carrier) and eventually shipped to its final destination.  END OF REPORT
column169: More community outreach and advertising to better inform shippers of the requirements of shipping hazmat.  END

CN transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car TILX 190461 during normal switching operations at the CN Glenn Yard, Chicago, IL. CN's response team responded noting three of the six manway bolts were less than tool tight allowing product to escape during movement. Manway bolts were properly secured and tank car was released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line as non-hazardous material by NYK, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Seoul Express from Savannah, Georgia to Tokyo, Japan.    NYK advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Savannah that the shipment was not booked as hazardous materials, the shipping papers did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials.    NYK subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

PLMX 23519 was noted by carrier personnel with product splashed on sides of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and tightened the manway cover bolts stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: NATX 71266 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, One Stop Environmental, responded and tightened one loose manway cover bolt stopping the vapor release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: CN transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car GATX 63208 during normal switching operations at the CN Champaign Yard, Urbana, IL. All appropriate departments were notified and tank car was isolated. CN response team responded noting the frangible disc was missing from the safety vent housing allowing product to escape during movement. Shipper's response team replaced safety vent housing,  frangible disc and tank car was released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: 2/16/08: At approximately 11:50AM, Hump Conductor noted tank car UTLX 668627, load Environmentally Hazardous Sustance, Liquid, NOS (Alcohol C12-C16, Poly 1-6 Ethoxylate), Class 9, UN 3082, PG III (Marine Pollutant), leaking from the top of the car as it passed through the retarders on its way to track 9 Class.    Further inspection by CR's A. Richter, Mgr. Risk Mgmt., and REACT Env. Services R. Gould found five (5) of six (6) manway cover bolts less than tool tight.  All swing bolts removed, manway cover opened and noted manway cover gasket in good condition.  Cover closed and all six manway cover bolts made secured.  Car okay for movement to original destination.    NOTE: In addition to the NJ DEP notification noted earlier in this report; Camden County Health, Env. and HazMat also notified by phone directly to E. Smith, by CR's A. Richter.    Also: 24-hour E.R. number (as noted on accompanying waybill) contacted was: 1-800-567-7455, by Pavonia Yardmaster at time of incident.    Original Manway cover seal "00623" removed during inspection; replaced with "REACT 001267.      Breadbox had no seal applied at initial inspection but after valves/fittings inspected inside (noted the 3" liquid valve closure plug not tool tight and secured during this inspection) was applied with seal "REACT 001269".    The bottom outlet closure plug required approximately 2 full turns by use of suitable tool to adequately secure the plug in place.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: UNIT BEING TRANSPORTED ON IR71 IN WARREN,OHIO, UNIT STOPPED BY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT, DUE TO MOTORIST COMPLANT, OFFICER SMELLED MERCAPTON COMING OFF TRAILER, OFFICER CALLED THE UNION TOWNSHIP VFD IN S.LEBANON,OH. THEY THEN CLOSED DOWN BOTH DIRECTIONS OFF IR71. FIRE DEPARTMENT SUITED UP AND CHECKED UNIT OUT, PRESSURE ON TRAILER SHOWNING 1 PSI. DRIVER OF UNIT HAD BEEN WATCHING THE PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER FOR THE LAST 4 DAYS AND THE PRESSURE HAD STAYED AT 4 1/2 PSI. COMPANY DISPATCH A EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE TO CHECK OUT THE LEAKING TRAILER.  ERT SUITED OUT AND CHECKED TRAILER PRESSURE ON GAUGE READING 4 1/2 PSI. TRAILER MOVED TO SCALE HOUSE ON IR71.TRAILER CLEANED ON THE OUTSIDE WITH BLEACH AND WATER. TRAILER THEN TESTED AND FOUND DOME LEAKING 345 PPM FROM THE GASKET. RELEAVED THE PRESSURE OFF THE TRAILER AND THE GASKET SHOWED 0 PPM COMING FROM THE DOME AREA. TRAILER RELEASED TO MAKE DELIVERY. STARTED THIS AT 1300 2/16/08, TRAILER REALEASED AT 1600 2/17/08

column168: A FRA inspector reported finding ACFX 82823 (a two compartment DOT 111A100W1 tank car) dripping product from one of the bottom outlet caps (BOC) during an inspection in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected ACFX 82823 and found product drips from the BOC for compartment 2. Product was building up around the BOC threaded connection and then dripping off. The responder tool tightened the BOC by less than a quarter turn and drippage ceased. Securement was completed by 1500 hrs. PST, 2/07/08. The bottom operated valve's operating handle was in the closed position. All spillage evaporated and no other securement deficiencies were noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 52903 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a product slosh from the manway cover during normal switching operations. The movement of GATX 52903 was immediately stopped, isolating GATX 52903 in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called to inspect GATX 52903. The BNSF responder reported finding no product wetness on the tank shell and no ground impact evident; but a dried residue product stain emanating from the manway nozzle. The responder found 4 of 8 manway securement bolts less than tool tight (only hand tight). The responder properly tool tightened the loose manway securement bolts. Response was concluded by 2145 hrs. PST, 2/13/08. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The shipment was booked with one item of hazardous material (UN1268, Petroleum Distillates, NOS, Class 3, PG III) for loading on the Hapag-Lloyd Container Line vessel Veracruz Express from Houston, Texas to Marsaxlokk, Malta.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Houston of the additional hazardous material (UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS, Class 3, PG II) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.      The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: A BNSF local train crew inspecting their train in the railyard prior to departure, observed UTLX 210737 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from its top fitting area. No ground impact of product was evident and all spillage on the side shell of UTLX 210737 evaporated.

column168: On 02/07/2008 at 00:04 hours, FRA inspector Hoose discovered TILX 190405, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S, leaking in the CSX Transportation rail yard in Lafayette, IN. The car was dripping product from the bottom outlet valve because the bottom valve operating handle was not secured and had fallen into the open position.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Cargill, Inc, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2008-02-12-00033). Sunpro, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that railroad personnel had closed the bottom outlet valve operating handle and pinned it in the closed position.  Contractor personnel removed the bottom outlet cap, turned over the cap gasket, and secured the cap wrench tight. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  580  NARRI:  5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: Tank unit was set lifted from vessel and landed on dock. Tank valve inadvertantly made contact with Inter Box Connector that was on the dock.  This forced the valve upward and caused a 1/4" x 3" split in the weld between the valve pipe and flange.  All personnel involved in the dock operation were temporarily evacuated to safe assembly area.  No injuries occured.  Seattle Fire Dept. responded and applied absorbant material around the damage, slowing the flow of liquid. Environmental contractor, National Response Company, transfered contents of damaged tank to a second tank provided by the shipper via pump. Residual material that could not be lifted by the pump was allowed to drain into a recovery drum.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: KENNY WAS EASTBOUND LOADED - PARKING DELIVERY TO BASALT. HE REACHED DOWN TO GRAB A MAP AND DRIFTED OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. HE OVER CORRECTED BACK TO THE LEDT AND OVERTURNED.  THE VEHICLE ROLLED 1/14 THURNS COMING TO REST AON ITS LEFT SIDE-FACING BACK TO WEST WITH THE TRACTOR PARTIALLY IN THE MEDIAN AN THE TRAILER BLOCKING THE LEFT EAST BOUND LANE. THE TRAILER DID NOT RUPTURE BUT WAS TORGHED ENOUGH THAT THE 5TH (REAR) COMP. DOME LID LEAKED-1000 TO 1200 GALLONS OF NO LEAD REGULAR GASOLINE WAS SPILLED ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THE GASOLINE RAN OFF BOTH SIDED OF THE ROADWAY TO RIGHT HAND BARROW DITCH AND TO THE MEDIAN. APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF THE GASOLINE WAS PUMPED INTO DRUMS.  RESPONSE: ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM SKIP WAS NOTIFIED AND CALLED RM CAT. I WAS NOTIFIED AT ABOUT 2:15 PM. I CALLED ECOS TO GET THEM TO GO TO SITE AND TO BEGIN EMERGENCY CONTAINMENT. I ALSO CALLED GJCT SHOP AND DISPATCHED EUGENE THOMPSON TO THE SITE WITH THE SERVICE TRK TO ASSIST IN TRANSFER OF PRODUCT. I CALLED JEREMY MERRIL (ACCT MGR) AND HAD HIM TRAVEL TO SITE FROM DR BEQUE TO SUPERVISE  UNTIL SKIP COULD ARRIVE FROM DENVER. JERRY & EUGENE ARRIVED AT ABOUT 4:30 AND REPORTED THAT EMERGENCY CONTAINMENT HAD BEE ESTABLISHED. RM CAT ARRIVED AT ABOUT 6 PM AND OPENED HOLES IN THE REIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK TO FACILITATE TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT. SKIP ARRIVED AT ABOUT THE SAME TIME AND TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT WAS BEGUN. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED BY ABOUT 7:30PM. THE WRECKED TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE UPRIGHT AND TOWED TO GLENWOOD SPRINGS.  RM CAT DID INITIAL CLEAN-UP OF THE ROADWAY AND IT WAS RE-OPENED AT ABOUT 10:30PM. SKIP TOOK KENNY TO THE GLENWOOD HOSPITAL FOR BLOOD ALCOHOL TEST WHICH WAS COMPLETED @ 11:48 PM. THAT WAS THE FIRST OPPORTUNITY TO GET THE TEST DONE AS THE HIGHWAY PATROL RELEASED HIM AFTER ACCIDENT WAS CLEANED UP.
IMPROPER LOADING PROCEDURES BY DOCK ASSOCIATES.

column168: DAVISON FURS TRUCK DRIVER WAS AT A DELIVERY LOCATION (A RETAIL GALOSINE STATION). THIS STATION WAS TWO REGULAR UNLEADED UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS. DRIVER BEGAN UNLOADING PROCESS AND WAS UNLOADING INTO BOTH TANKS. THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSES WERE CONNECTED FROM TANKS TO TRANPORT VEHICLE.  JUST BEFORE UNLODING WAS COMPLETE.  SOME GASOLINE WAS FORCED OUT OF THE COUPLING OF THE TANKS FILL PIPE AND THE TRANPORT VEHICLES UNLOADING LOCK DOWN (A CO-AXIAL DROP FITTING). DRIVER NOTION LEAKAGE IMMEDIATLY AND SHUT DOWN UNLOADING. VERY LITTLE PRODUCT WAS LOST ESTIMATED UNDER FOUR GALLONS.  FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTION AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP USING OIL ESTER ABSURBANT.  DRIVER FOUND THAT PRESSURE HAS BUILT UP IN TANKS AND TO THE TANKS VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM NOT OPENING PROPERLY.  ONE PRESSURE WAS REDUCED THRU VAPOR SYSTEM UNLOADING PROCESS WITH NO PROBLEMS. THE RELOCATION PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND WAS ON A CONCRETE SURFACE. NO PRODUCT CONTACTED ANY SOIL.
column169: VAPOR RECOVERY SYTEM AT THIS LOCATION IS UNDERGROUND AND THE TANK PIPES ARE CONNECT TO ALLOW VAPORS TO BE COLLECTED AT ONE COMMON POINT. THE POINT IS WHERE DRIVER CONNECTS HIS VAPOR RECOVERY HOSES AND RUNS FROM BAR TO THE TRUCK. THERE IS NO WAY TO TELL IF VAPOR SYSTEM IN TANKS IS OPERATIONAL (BY DRIVER). AS NO VAPOR IS ALLOWED TO ESCAPE TO STATION OWNER WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT AND HE WILL HAVE QUALIFIED TECHNICIANS CHECK HIS TANKS AND CORRECT THE PROBLEM.

column168: Our investigation indicates that the probable cause for the spill was a secondary system (hydraulic) failed or "bled" back causing the secondary valves to prematurely close.  Valves were left open to drain the compartments.  Upon pumping the hydraulic system up, material that remained in two of the three comparments emptied from them.  Once this happened the valves at the two compartments were closed, the material on the pavement was contained and the clean up began.  Material was collected and placed into open head 55 gallon plastic drums.  The drums were set into the proper hazardous waste storage area and will be shipped off site for disposal.
column169: Employees will be trained to close compartment valves as they are emptied and to not drain them down as is practiced at this time.  This will eliminate a secondary valve failure resulting in a spill in this manner in the future.  Material remaining in compartments will be confirmed visually before they are properly closed for transportation.

column168: On 2-11-08 around 1030 hours, TASD switching crew discovered and reported to the TASD yardmaster that ECUX 355113, loaded tank car was leaking from the top area of the car in track 17 on the north end of the TASD interchange. Track 17 was pulled out of service and I proceeded to the car and placed a recptacle under the leak around 1145. I then contacted SWS Co. and gave them all info on the leak. SWS arrived around 1330 hours and tracks were locked and flagged by TASD Carmen on duty and SWS employees began work on the car. SWS employees discovered a 3" top ball valve handle was loose. They tightened the valve packing gland nut and closed the valve and observed valve for sometime allowing pressure to build up. No product leaked from the valve stem or the ball as it had done before. Spillage on side of car was padded off as well as the valve stem and plug. SWS stated that due warmer temperatures, pressure built up in the car forcing product out of the 3" valve stem and plug. SWS completed repairs around 1600 same day.
column169: All valve handle bolts and packing need to be checked before departing loading facility.

Driver arrived at plant and was directed to loading rack. Driver preformed walk around on trailer to look for any problems. During this walk around he opened the internal and external valve on the trailer to inspect them. Driver left the valves open and went on top of trailer and began inspecting the trailer and getting prepared to begin loading process. This is a facility that requires the driver to do all the loading himself. The driver spent some time on top of trailer to familiarize himself with the loading process. While doing this the driver forgot that he had left the valves open on the rear of the trailer. The driver began loading the product into the tank, and realized he had left the valves open. The driver shut down the product and ran to the rear of the trailer and shut the valves. Before he could get the valves shut 70 gallons of product had leaked on the ground.

On 02/07/08 at 0145 personnel in the CSXT, Willard, OH terminal discovered a defective "R" side door on TIMX 65759, a loaded boxcar of calcium carbide tote bins. The car was bad ordered and the car was not sent over the yard hump. The shipper was notified via Chemtrec, and the car was isolated on the shop track. CSXT Hazmat manager T. J. Mannas inspected TIMX 65759 on 02/15/08, and noted one of the tote bins protruding from the "R" side door approximately 24 inches. The entire load (32 bins in 2 x 16 pattern) had shifted. A "toe" board (2" x 10" on edge) at the base of the "R" side door was splintered by the protruding tote bin. A tarp was placed over the "R" side door to prevent moisture from entering TIMX 65759. T. Mannas discussed this with Elkem Metal Company personnel at Pittsburgh, PA and Ashtabula, OH. Dryburg Company, Pittsburgh, PA personnel and Eagle Construction + Environmental Services (ECESI), Findlay, OH personnel along with T. Mannas opened the "L" side door on 02/19, 2008. A completely deflated D.I.D (disposable inflatable dunnage) as blocking and bracing was found in the center of the load. The D.I.D. was punctured. Several of the tote bins inside TIMX 65759 had released product inside the boxcar. No product had exited the boxcar. On 02/25/08, T. Mannas met Elkem Metal Company, Ashtabula, OH representative and ECESI representative. All concurred that the transfer and repair of the containers should not be attempted until weather conditions permit, (i.e. no  rain nor snow). Additional information will be provided in a supplemental DOT 5800 report.      SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION:  ON 04/08/2008 AT 0730 HOURS, ELKEM METALS, INC., ASHTABULA, OH PERSONNEL LEAD BY MR. M. SIMONS AND ASSISTED BY EAGLE CONSTRUCTION & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (ECESI), FINDLAY, OH, TRANSFERRED TOTE BINS FROM TIMX 65759 ONTO FOUR FLAT BED TRUCKS. DEFECTIVE TOTE BINS WERE REPAIRED BY ELKEM METALS, INC. PERSONNEL. APPROXIMATELY 600 POUNDS OF CALCIUM CARBIDE HAD LEAKED FROM 7 OF 32 TOTE BINS. ORIENTED FROM B TO A END, R AND L SIDES, THE TOTE BINS THAT LEAKED WERE: L7, R8, L10, R10, L11, R12 AND L14.
column169: At this time, we cannot determine exactly how many totes have leaked, nor the amount spilled. However, all material is contained within the boxcar. A supplemental DOT 5800 will follow after product (container) transfer.

column168: On February 28, 2008 at approximately 0830, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered TILX303032, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia leaking vapo rfrom the Pressure Relief Device. The car was isolated and the shipper (CHEMTREC Report #2008-02-28-00045) and State Of Ohio EPA  were notified. Veolia Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the O-rings on the PRD were deteriorated and resulted in a slight vapor leak. Contractor personnel replaced the o-rings and checked for further leaks after repair. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  414  NARRI:  5 (5+9+0) X (2+0) = 140
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While enroute to the consignee, the driver was inspecting the trailer at one of our facilities and noticed a little product in the crash box.  The dome closure had a seal on it so the driver got permission from the shipper to break the seal and tighten a dogear on the dome that had loosened up allowing a little product to leak out.
column169: Driver secured the dogear and wiped the product out of the crash box.  There was no further sign of any leakage.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: Our company was hired to pick up an intermodal shipment at the NS rail facility in Harrisburg, Pa, This was a sealed unit . Our driver did his pre trip inspection of the equipment,(not allowed to open the unit because of the seal) and departed the rail facility with the intermodal container, less than a mile from the ramp he felt the load shift,he stop his truck and the load was moving side to side, he felt if he lowered his landing gear to the ground it would secure the load, as opposed to his air ride suspension. He moved to a safe area and dropped the unit, the load shift was so bad it caused the trailer to fall over. Our driver secured the scene and call Chemtrec and the 911 and our office, we dispatched help to the scene..once on the scene we spoke to the shipper to find that they had given us the incorrect paper work, this caused some delay, once the proper paper work was sent the unit was opened and what was found was twelve bins that had been loaded down the center of the trailer with no blocking and bracing for side movement, which caused the load to go over, the cargo was on one side.The release was 450 gallons contained to an area of 20 ft.. long and three feet wide, it was controlled by absorbent material.The clean up took many hours due to the nature of the equipment needed to transtoad the product. This entire incident is a result of not securing the loaded it original in CA.The package failure was a result of the cargo not being blocked and braced.we have pictures of all events...
column169: The issue for our company as an intermodal drayman .We receive pre loaded equipment from domestic suppliers orinternationals suppliers and have to count on them to make sure the load is properly loaded and secured, we received a sealed unit and under the terms of the bill of lading contract we can not break the seal.I believe the shippers that cause these issues should be held responsible for all costs and be forced to follow the lawfor cargo securementWe should not be the one that has to fight the tickets and the court case to defend our position...we did nothing wrong other than trust that this shipper followed the law, which they did not.

column168: EVENT # 21212    SPILL - LOADED/HAZ, D/R SIGNED, FULL PPE YES, W/C CLR/DRY. ID REPT APROX 350 GAL’S OF PRODUCT SPILLED FROM TRLR INTERNAL VALVE ONTO CEMENT IN A CONTAIN AREA. ID STATED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT PUT TOGETHER CORRECTLY. CUSTOMER WILL CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

Operators began the process of off loading a tank trailer through a transfer pipe from the trailer to the container fill room at approximately 14:15 PM. During the container filling process the operator noticed a drop in material volume,checked the transfer line and discovered an open valve.Aluminum Sulfate 48% leaked from a damaged 1.5 inch drain valve located in the transfer line. Prior to unloading the tank trailer, operators discovered that the three 1.5 inch drain valves in the transfer line were frozen in the open position. Steam was applied to the valves and apparently when the operator closed the valves the stem connecting the ball assembly to the handle broke on one of the valves, this allowed the handle to turn to the closed position and the ball assembly to remain in the open position.The Aluminum Sulfate leaked into a swale area of approximately 3,300 sq. ft. UNIVAR employees responded by covering spill and creating a dam of Soda Ash to contain and neutralize the material. Our Emergency Response Contractor responded with heavy equipment and secured the spill and began the recovery process. Due to theweather conditions (temperatures in the thirties and snow on the ground) the Aluminum Sulfate tended to solidify assisting in the clean up process. The contractor was able to scoop up the material and contaminated soils into sixcontainers totaling approximately 200 tons, they remained on site until the evening of February 2 to ensure all cleanup was completed.
column169: The CPVC transfer pipeline that connects the tank trailer unloading area to the container fill room is approximately 200 feet long and has three drain valves in the line to allow drainage of residues. After each use the line is flushed with water to prevent cross contamination of materials. Our investigation of this incident has determined that due to weather conditions the water flushed through the line after the prior use froze in the drain valves. The use of the steam in the thawing process damaged the valve components allowing the handle to indicate the valve was closedwhile the ball assembly remained in the open position.New drain valves have been purchased and will be removed after the pipeline is flushed. Valves will be stored in aheated location when the line is not in use and will be reinstalled prior to the pipeline being used for material transfer.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a pail that was slightly leaking from the bottom. column169: Before placing material on pallets always inspect the pallets to insure that nothing like a nail is protruding from it that could possible damage commodities staged on them.

column60: Gouged or Cut; Ripped or Torn
column168: TRANSPORT DRIVER TURNED TOO CLOSE TO A CAR CARRIER AND RAMP ON CAR CARRIER WENT INTO SIDE OF TANKER TRAILER RESULTING IN A 6-INTCH TEAR IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER SHELL. 384 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED IN TOTAL. APPROX 40 GALLOSNS WERE CAUGHT IN A REFUSE CAN AND THE REMAINDER SPILLED ON THE GROUND. THE PRODUCT COVERED A LARGE AREA OF THE PARKING LOT AND ALSO RAN INTO THREE STORM WATER CATCHMENT BASINS. THE PRODUCT MOVED THROUGH A COMMON PIPE CONNECTING THE BASINS AND TERMINATED APPROX. 300 FEET WHERE A RETENTION POND FOR STORM WATER IS LOCATED. THERE WAS APPROX. A FOOT OF WATER COVERING THE FLOOR OF THE POND AND WATER SHOWED A SHEEN OF OIL OVER THE SURFACE.  THE POND OUT FALL WAS FLOWING WATER OUT OF THE POND TO A STREAM THAT CONTINUED UNDER ROUTE 30 AND DOWN TO WOLFE ROAD. SEE ENCLOSED MAP FOR LOCATIONS.AERO PERSONNEL COVERED ASPHALT WITH SORBENT AND INSTALLED SORBENT BOOMS IN TWO LOCATIONS IN CREEK, (SEE ATTACHED MAP FOR LOCATION). THE OUTFALL OF WATER IN THE CONTAINMENT POND WAS SLOWED BY PLUGGING WITH BOOM MATERIAL AND SWEEPS WERE PLACED ON THE SURFACE TO ABSORB OIL PRESENT. WE ALSO PLACED SORBENT SWEEPS AND BOOMS IN TWO LOCATIONS IN THE CREEK TO CATCH ANY OIL THAT WAS PRESENT. (SEE ENCLOSED PICTURES). RESPONSE PERSONNEL/CONTRACTORS WERE CONTACTED EARLY ON AND ARRIVED ON SITE AT 24:00 HOURS WITH VARIOUS EQUIPMENT INCLUDING A VACUUM TRUCK AND MATERIALS TO REMOVE OIL PRESENT.  I HAVE ENCLOSED A COPY OF THE WORK DONE AND THE PLAN FOR FOLLOW UP BUY A&A ENVIRONMENTAL. A LARGE QUANTITY OF THE SPILLED FUEL WAS RECOVERED BY FLUSHING ALL OF THE STRORM WATER BASINS AND DRAIN PIPES TO THE POND IN FALL WHERE IT WAS VACUUMED AND REMOVED. AERO PERSONNEL CONTINUED TO SWEEP UP DEPLOYED ABSORBENT AND ABSORBED OIL  ALL MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL. THE TOTALQUANTITY OF ABSORBENT USED WAS 50 BAGS. THE PROCESS OF CLEANNING UP THE AVSORBENT WAS COMPLETED AT 10:00 AM ON 2/27/08.  AERO ENERY PERSONNEL RESPONDING TO SITE: JIM O'BRIEN, JIM RABINE, RON GROFT, JIM O'BRIEN JR., FRANK PINTER, TOM WASHBURN. CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR RESPONDING TO SITE: A&A ENVIRONMENTAL, 1500 CARBON AVE., BALTIMORE, MD 21226 CONTACT TOM RUSH @ 410-636-2294.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a box that was on a pallet that was leaking. Further investigation revealed that the pallet had been pushed into the pallet in front of it and as a result a can that was in a box staged on the pallet was crushed and contributed to the unintentional release.
column169: Material handlers need to look at the big picture and understand their clearances when it comes to loading freight and not push freight into each other. This is a good example of what can happen if you do that when loading freight and will be used as a training toolto prevent future occurences.

column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: On 2/21/2008, I took a call from a person named Josh who indicated that he believed his shipment contained undeclared dangerous goods. Josh gave me the tracking # and I found it was loaded in an AKE ULD on FedEx flight 1413 MEM - HNL. At the time ofthe discovery the flight was four hours out from HNL. Along with FedEx Flight Safety & Global Operations Control we decided to let the aircraft continue to the destination while advising the crew. That decision was based on the fact that since the aerosols were a non-flammable gas and could be loaded inaccessible to the crew, it made no sense to land at an airport that wasn't on the flight plan. The flight landed without incident and the shipment was recovered from the ULD. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Mike Givens in LAX. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection that was completed by FAA SA Tony Tepedino. There were no markings,labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated.

THE FUEL CONTROL UNIT IN THE BOX WASN'T PROTECTED FROM LEAKING. THERE WAS NO BARRIER BAG NOR ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE PACKAGING. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION, NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA HAS BEEN NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA JIM BERK. SA BERK REQUESTED THAT FEDEX TAKE PICTURES OF THE SHIPMENT & IT'S CONTENTS. THOSE PICTURES WILL BE FORWARDED VIA EMAIL TO SA BERK. THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE FAA.

WHEN THE BOX WAS UNLOADED FROM A ULD, THE FIBREBOARD MATERIAL RIPPED AWAY AS THE BOX WAS TOO HEAVY. THE BOX CONTAINED A CAN OF BONDO, AN AUTOMOTIVE DENT REPAIR MATERIAL. THE LABEL ON THE BONDO CAN INDICATES FLAMMABLE VAPORS. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA DAVID HENDRICKS. THE FREIGHT WAS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a client location. Upon arriving the driver had the client sign off on a product integrity form. The form stated that 7005 gallons of ULSD was to be delivered to the above ground 10000 gallon tank. Once the driver had done this he began to unload. As the driver finished unloading he began to walk his hose to ensure that the remaining fuel in the hose was out, fuel began to leak out of the tank vent. Driver immediately stopped draining the hose but approximately 20-30 gallons had leaked in to the concrete area around the tank. No product reached soil or drains. The customer and driver used saw dust to absorb the spill. The saw dust was then placed into a 55 gallon drum for disposal by the customer.

column168: Intermodal container MSKU 660114 was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance after its arrival on a BNSF intermodal train. MSKU 660114 was carefully moved to the containment area for inspection of the lading within. Shipper contract responders reported finding one 275 gallon IBC (UN specification 31H1) that was compromised during a load shift inside this container during transportation. The IBC's outer tubular metal cage was damaged with a portion breaking and puncturing the upper corner of this rigid plastic IBC. The puncture hole was plugged/patched using absorbent pads and sealed with duct tape. An application of floor dry was used on the container floor to absorb spillage. The initial spillage on the ground (estimated at one pint) and the spillage outside MSKU 660114 in the containment area (estimated at one quart) was also cleaned. The lading around the damaged IBC was adjusted to prevent further shifting. All cleaning material used and spent absorbent was placed into a savage drum liner and then placed inside the container. Afterwards, MSKU 660114 was released to the outbound drayage trucker for haulage to their facility for furtherance.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: A van trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. accepted for transportation 4 cubic yard IBC containers of spent carbon for disposal.  During the course of transportation, the shipment was stored in-transit at Clean Harbors' service center located in West Sacramento, CA.  During the course of this temporary storage, it was discovered that the 4 container developed a minor release whereby approximatley 1 liter in total escaped from the package onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel, using suitable protective equipment inspected the containers and determined that a small amount of residual water separated from the solid material and escaped through a pinhole leak in the liner of the IBC.  A suitable absorbent material was added to the containers to absorb all freee liquids and the clear liquid that was relesed was observed and placed into a suitable container and was sent for disposal along with the original containers.  The containers were observed and was determined that the leak had been stopped and contained.  Once secured, the containers were sent to the intended waste management facility for disposal.
column169: At the time the container were accepted for transportation, no evidence of residula liquids was observed and the containers appeared to be intact and non-leaking.  The shipper of the material was contacted and it is believed that the material in question was removed from the filter press and immediatley containerized rather than allowing a suitable amount of time to completely dry out.  During the course of transportation, it is believed that residual liquid believed to be water separated from the solid material and leaked from the package.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper will insure that the material, once removed from the filter press, is affored enough time to dry before containerizing and sending for disposal.  In addition, the drivers will continue to inspect each container as it is loaded and take appropriate actions should a leaking ro damaged container be encountered.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc, Driver was unloading unleaded gas at a customer location. Upon arriving the driver took readings that indicated he had room to unload 6407 gallons into tank 1 and 4249 gallons into tank 2. After unloading 3000 gallons into tank 1 the driver unloaded 4000 gallons into tank 2. While unloading the driver noticed product leaking from tank 2. The driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 108 gallons had leaked onto the containment area, not reaching soil. The amount of product lost was based on the variance from what was already unloaded and what was retained on the truck. A small amount of fuel did get into the drain. SWS First Response was called to the scene and was able to clean up the remaining product. The customer, QT, was notified and their environmental representative was onsite for the clean-up.
column169: The customer was notified of the tank problem and will have the maintenance needed to repair the tank completed. The customer will have a representative onsite for the next delivery.

column168: The tractor-tube trailer was traveling WB on I-84.  The vehicleleft the road into the median striking a guardrail and then overturning.  As a result of the accident a tube valve was cracked at the stem resulting a a slow release of hydrogen from one tube on the trailer.  All tube valves were closed as were the manifold valves.  As a precaution, emergency crews evacuated the immediate area.  A team from Linde was dispatched to the scene and prior to uprighting the trailer, vented remaining hydrogen through a stack and then purged the tubes with nitrogen.  There was not a fire or other adverse event after the rolo over.
column169: At this time it is difficult to determine if better packaging would have prevented the release of product.  The release was the result of a very severe accident.  The pakage and valve functioned properly in conditions normally incident to transportation.

column168: A tank trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route to the intended destination facility when a drip was identified coming from the rear valve of the tank trailer.  The vehicle was moved to a secured location  and a containmnet device was plced udner the valve to collect any material that escaped from the valve.  A maintenance crew was dispatched to the scene and it was discovered that a loose bolt, not evident at the time the driver departed for the trip allowed a small amount of product to drip from the rear valve.  The service technician tightented all bolts and the leak was stopped.  The truck was followed to the destination facility where the contents were unloaded.  After the vehicle was off-loaded, the trailer was placed out of service pending an inspection of the rear valve assembly.  Upon inspection, it was determined that the components of the valve did not fail but rather a bolt of the flange became loose due to what is believed to be vibration of the value during loading.  The valve was re-assembled and all bolts tightened according to all required specifications.  Due to the minimal amount actually released, there was no clean-up required.
column169: AT the time of loaidng, the driver inspected the vehicle and no evidence of leakage was observed.  In order to prevent a recurence, the driver has been re-instructed to insure that a proper pre-trip inesection is performed and any deficiency noted and addressed prior to departure.  IN addition, the driver has been reminded to take all appropriate measures should an issue be discovered during routine load inspections while in transit.

column168: On 02/14/2008 unit #597 drifted off the right shoulder of the road. When he pulled the truck back onto the roadway he over corrected causing both units to roll over in the ditch. During the course of the accident the body tank became dislodged form the truck causing the fire valve to be damaged. This was the only point of failure. There were no other points of failure other then cosmetic damage. Absorbent pillows and snakes were to contain the oil. The bulk of the spill occurred when the fire valve was removed to evacuate the product from the tank. We had in place another of our tankers and a vac truck to pick up the leaking oil. Power Fuels was contacted and returned with another vac truck and hot oil trucks to steam and clean up the affected area. Reference: #28 On the second unit (#2) the trailer, all that is on the spec plate for a manufacture date is 04/1979.The last test date for #2 is 06/04/2007
column169: There wasn't a problem with the tanks, they held up well. This was a driver error issue. All our drivers have been informed that they must pay more attention to what is going on around them. The driver was wearing his seat belt and was not injured.

column168: Two (2) 55-gallon drums of an acidic liquid were shipped by a common carrier from our Luling, LA plantto our laboratories in St. Louis, MO. When the dock personnel moved the pallet in the truck, they noticed that the drums had leaked while in transport. The tops of the drums and an approximate 10X6 foot section of the trailer floor were wet (estimated spill 500-1000 ml).The dock personnel notified our site security office who notified our site safety group. The site safety responders tightened the bungs on the drums. They then used sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the liquid on the drums and the truck bed. All materials were swept up, cleaned and appropriately disposed.When the floor bed was dry, the carrier left the site and the drums were delivered to the intended recipient on the site.Upon investigation, it was determined that while the closure instructions for the drums were available and followed, the torque setting on the wrench was set incorrectly (9 Ibs/ft versus 20 Ibs/ft in the instructions).
column169: We will institute a check list with a check off boxes to verify compliance. A second person will be responsible for reviewing the closure procedures and the torque wrench settings. We will add a tamper-proof seal to bung openingsand verify the filling of the drums to ensure the proper fill levels (outage and ullage). Communication of the changes will be made to all shippers and the rest of our sites.

column168: PACKAGE CONTAINED 1 4-LITER GLASS BOTTLE WHICH CRACKED AT THE BOTTOM. THE OUTER CARTON HAD BURST AT THE BOTTOM. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THRU THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.
PACKAGE CONTAINED 4 1-GALLON BOTTLES IN WHICH ONE HAD LEAKED AT THE CLOSURE. THE OUTER CARTON WAS SOILED AT THE TOP. THEDAMAGED PORTION WAS PROCESSED THRU THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

BOBTAIL WAS TRAVELING ON VINE STREET TO MAKE A DELIVERY. EMPLOYEE HAS STATED THAT HIS SPEED WAS APPROXIMATELY 45 MPH. EMPLOYEE GAVE THE REASON FOR THE BOBTAIL ROLL OVER AS MECHANICAL FAILURE WITH THE FRONT BRAKES. ADAM STATED THAT WHEN HE "PRESSED ON THE BRAKE PEDAL THAT THE STEERING WHEEL PULLED TO THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL TO LEAVE THE ROAD SURFACE AND GO ON TO THE SHOULDER OR THE ROAD. ADAM STATED THAT HE TRIED TO STEER THE VEHICLE BACK ON TO THE PAVEMENT BUT THAT IS WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER.  BASIC CAUSES: SPEED MAY HAVE BEEN A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR. MR. SANDERS STATED THAT HE WAS DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 45 MPH AND THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT IS 35 MPH. THE DRIVER MAY HAVE LOST ATTENTION TO HIS DRIVING CAUSING THE FRONT WHEEL OF THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROAD SURFACE AND TRAVELED ON THE THE SHOULDER. INSTEAD OF ALLOWING THE VEHICLE TO SLOW DOWN AND RE-GAIN CODNTROL OF THE VEHICLE, ADAM PANICKED AND TRIED TO SUDDENLY STEER THE VEHICLE FROM THE SHOULDER ON THE ROADWAY. THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO LOOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND A ROLL-OVER OCCURRED.
column169: SSM TO REVIEW ACCIDDNT PREVENTION VIDEO WITH ALL EMPLOYEES. VIDEO DISCUSSES WHAT TO DO IN THE EVENT OF DUALS LEAVING THE PAVED ROAD-CORRECTIVE ACTION TO TAKE. SSM TO REENFORCE ON A DAILY BASIS USE OF SEAT BELTS AND MONITOR SUCH US.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During a routine inspection of the trailer, while at the Norfolk Southern Railyard in Chicago, Illinois, a leak was discovered.  Trailer was secured, a Material Safety Data Sheet was referenced, and SET Environmental, Inc. of Bridgeview, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, SET Environmental, Inc. discovered one (1) steel tote, had a faulty weld on the drainage valve, which resulted in the release.  Approximately 5 gallons of free product were released to the trailer floor, and a minimal amount affected the gravel surface beneath the trailer.  SET Environmental, Inc. proceeded to apply oil dry to the free product, which was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, along with the cleanup materials, pending disposal.  SET Environmental, Inc. proceeded to pump the remaining product from the damaged tote, into a compatible replacement tote, and one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum.  Two (2) 55-gallon recovery drums will be disposed of in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  The compatible tote was sent along with the remainder of the shipment for disposition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty valve, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Triple Crown Services will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Before transferring product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank, the driver took a sample from the bleeder valve on the dischange valve of the cargo tank.  He closed the bleeder valve but forgot to close the internal valve.  When he took the cap off of the discharge valve to hook up the hose, product ran out. He was able to close the internal valve to stop the product release. The spill was on concrete and shoveled into drums.
column169: The driver did not follow procedure.  He is scheduled for performance enhancement training.

column168: Univar driver picked up 2 cubic yard boxes and 12 drums of waste from generator.  When driver arrived at next pickup, noticed a small leak from one of the cubic yard boxes.  Small leak was contained using floor absorbant materials by Univar employees.  The generator was notified of the leak in the packaging. The box was then over packaged into an approved overpackaging bag.   Absorbant materials were used to clean up spilled materials, and box was returned to generator by Univar driver.      Leak was determined to be caused by thin metal strips placed into the box with waste items.  The thin metal strips tore the liner placed inside the box, and allowed liquids to leak.
column169: Cubic yard box to be repackaged by generator without metal strips which could cause tears to the liners.  Sharp items and strips should be packaged in containers resistant to tears.

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OFCHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by OOCL, on behalf of their shipper, with three items of the following hazardous materials for loading on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Yorktown Express from Houston, Texas.- UN2794, Batteries, Wet, Filled with Acid, Class 8- UN1268, Petroleum Distillates, NOS, Class 3, PGII- UN2049, Diethylbenzene, Class 3, PG III, Marine Pollutant OOCL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed Houston that UNI 170, Ethyl Alcohol, Class 3, PG II was also loaded in the freight container.The shipping papers accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the additional item.OOCL subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers. Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the additional item loaded in the container.

column168: THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL ON FEBRUARY 7, 2008, WAS CAUSED BY THE VEOLIA DRIVER NOT PERFORMING HIS JOB PROPERLY. AFTER LOADING, HE DID NOT SECURE THE CENTER DOME LID ON THE TANKER AND ALSO DID NOT PUT NUMBERED SEAL TIES ON THE LID. AFTER THE DRIVER LEFT THE PLANT, HE REALIZED MATERIAL WAS RUNNING DOWN THE EXTERNAL WALLS OF THE TANKER INTO THE HOSE TRAYS AND ONTO THE ROAD. HE STOPPED AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED. THE LOUISVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE METROPOLITAN SEWER DISTRICT, AND A VEOLIA CELANUP CREW RESONDED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP PROCESS. APPROXIMATELY 50-100 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND INTO THE CATCH BASIN. THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY 4:00 P.M.
column169: THE RECOMMENDATIONS AND ACTION TAKEN ARE AS FOLLOWS: 1. TERMINATED THE DRIVER CAUSING THE DISCHARGE BECAUSE HE VIOLATED COMPANY POLICY.2. MET WITH A DRIVERS RE-EMPHASIZING THEIR RESPONSIBILITIES AND THE DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS VEOLIA WILL TAKE IF THE POLICY IS NOT FOLLOWED.A. TIGHTEN ALL DOME LIDS PRIOR TO MOVING THE UNIT.B. ATTACH PLASTIC NUMBER SEAL STRIPS TO ALL DOME LIDS AND VALVE CAPS.C. LIST THE SEAL NUMBERS ON THE MANIFESTS.3. DRIVERS WHO DO NOT FOLLOW THE PROCEDURES WILL BE DISCHARGED EVEN IF A SPILL DOES NOT OCCUR.4. JOB SUPERVISORS, DISPATCH PERSONNEL, AND MANAGERS ARE RESPONSIBLE TO CHECKLOADED TANKERS ON A RANDOM BASIS.

column168: Our customer was unloading a pallet of three 55 gallon drums of Phosphoric Acid 85% off the back of the trailer with a forklift.  During the movement from the trailer the a drum shifted and fell from approximately dock high to the ground.  The drum ruptured and was completely spilled.  The product was completely contained.  Our driver assisted with controlling the incident, neutralizing the material, and cleanup.  All material was recovered into a 55 gallon open head poly drum.  No person was injured nor any equipment damaged.

column168: Driver arrived at the customer to off load 4,850 gallons of HCL.  Once all connections were made correctly the driver pressured the trailer utilizing tractor air and began off loading the product.  Forty minutes into unloading the driver went on top of the trailer to check all connections and gauges when the product hose from the rear of the trailer came apart at the bands of the hose.  The driver utilized the emergency shut off valve to stop the acid from spraying.  All acid was contained in the customer’s containment area.  The customer was able to handle the clean up by neutralizing the spilled with caustic soda.
column169: The hose had recently been banded by an outside repair shop.  Once the cause of the spill was determined the repair shop was contacted.  Presently all hoses that are used in our acid applicaiton are banded in two spots to connect the hose to the fitting.  All bands will be taken off all hoses and a crimping method will be utilized to better secure the hose to the flange.

column169: ONLY DAYLIGHT DELIVERIES PERMITTED AFTER THIS INCIDENT.

column168: On 2-26-08 around 1730 hours Job # 9 reported to the control station that the SHPX 202454 was leaking from the bottom outlet valve area on the south end of track 28 in the TASD Interchange. This car was interchanged from the NS RR to the AGR RR on the same date as the incident. The TASD Carmen locked and flagged track 28 and a bucket was placed under the valve. I then notified SWS Co. around 1900 and the response crew arrived around 1945 and proceeded to the tank car. SWS discovered the 4" bottom outlet cap was extremely loose. The cap was removed and the fluid was put into the 5 gallon bucket. The cap gasket and valve was inspected and appeared to be be in good condition. The cap was wiped dry and put back on and tightened down with a three foot pipe wrench and was observed for leaks. No leaking was discovered and the car was released back into service around 2130.
column169: Outlet caps and all valves should be checked before departing loading facilities.

column168: Cargo tank was pretripped before bringing it to the shipper to load.  Driver and loader were on top of cargo tank during loading.  When they came down they noticed a puddle under the bleeder valve on the discharge assembly.  The handle had evidently vibrated loose and allowed some product to escape.  The internal valve was then reseated to make sure it was holding before the trailer was moved. Spill occurred in a containment area.

column168: The Employee was filling a forklift cylinder at a Commercial/Industrial customer location.  When the Employee stopped filling, the spring which holds up the fill valve that prevents propane from coming out broke.  The Employee states that this happened due to normal wear and tear and that the cold weather was a contributing factor.  There was no way to stop the release which was occurring in an open area away from any potential danger.  The Employee tipped the tank over and let the propane release the entire contents into a snow bank.
column169: The cylinder was taken back to the Service Unit for repairs.

column168: Driver gauged tanks and got unload hose hooked up, turned on electric pump, opened valve on pumpthen opened butterfly valve on trailer. He then went to control box and pulled air valves to open ventand DOT valve at this time oil sprayed from around load hose connection and trailer connection. Heshut everything down, pulled hose loose to inspect gasket. With wind blowing he could not hearpossible suction/air leak in connection. It's dark 12:30 AM, working lights on and hard to see gasket nick in the fitting on the hose and wear on the trailer fitting.Send out a safety letter to all of the terminals to re-enforce the need to check all gaskets and fittings atcustomer unload sites as well as our own equipment.

column168: Driver hooked up, and filled the trailer for mixing. When the trailer finished filling and pressured up,driver saw a puddle of water forming out to the side of the trailer. He shut down the pump, inspectedthe top of the trailer, but could not find the leak. He started the pump again, saw water spraying, he shutdown the pump, got mine personal to run the pump, while he stood on top of the trailer to locate theeak. He found a pinhole leak on a 2" nipple fitting that screw inside the tank. They shut down theiump, and washed down the trailer. He called dispatch and got permission for the mine maintenance toeld the leak. He finished mixing without any more problems. All the cyanide that leaked, about Gallon according to he was inside of the containment pad, which was washed down into the sump and pumped into mine tankage. Trailer was blue tagged upon return to yard and is waiting to be repaired.
column169: Not only this employee, but all employees will be required request the operator leave the walkway inthe down position to allow drivers to properly check vents, valves, and closure devices, prior toaccepting shipments. Refresher training will be administered 2-16-08. Employee will attend B.B.Straining in March. Peer review will be shared with other employees, along with the DuPont reviewonce it is received.

column168: The jerrican was placed on the dock at the carriers facility and subsequently struck by the carriers forklift operator while moving other freight. The freight struck the jerrican smashing it into the steel column supporting the wall. No structural damage to the building occurred but the contents of the jerrican were emptied onto the dock. The carriers supervisor notified the shipper who in turn contacted an emergency response contractor. The contractor arrived to the scene at the carriers facility at 0030 performed the necessary cleanup and departed at 0130. The contractor left the clean up material at the carriers facility and later retrievd. The release was managed in 5 hours to completion after the initial notification. This incident will exceed $500. The carrier is awaiting the final contractor report and invoicing from the shipper. The carrier will file an ammended report upon receipt of final report.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUS1 BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MW PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT DRUMS OF LIQUIDS ARE AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTIOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! column168: A BNSF switch crew reported SCMX 4324 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) dripping product in the railyard from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area with subsequent product evaporation. BNSF contract responders after inspecting SCMX 4324 reported product seepage was observed between the tank car's belly flange and the BOV mounting flange with no other securement exceptions noted. It was suspected that the gasket seal failed.  A vacuum truck pulled the vacuum from SCMX 4324 and the product drips subsided. SCMX 4324 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with a containment pool placed under SCMX 4324. On 2/21/08 by 1600 hrs. CST, all the remaining contents of SCMX 4324 was transferred into tanker trucks without further incident. No measurable product heel was observed afterwards, but a bag of oil dry was poured into SCMX 4324 to ensure the interior of SCMX 4324 was liquid free. All used absorbent pads and a small amount of liquid product collected from the containment pool were placed into a 55 gallon recovery drum for appropriate disposal. SCMX 4324 was forwarded to a qualified tank car repair facility to determine root cause of this leak. The last tank qualification of SCMX 4324 was completed in the year 2001 and next due in the year 2011.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Driver loaded #1 comaprtment with 3400 gallons of gasoline, when finished he noticed product leaking from under the tank. He notified the terminal operator and together they connected the trailer and off loaded #1 comaprtmnet while still at the load rack. An investigation found, the trailer has rain water drains passing trough #1 comaprtment from the top of the trailer. A drain had clogged and trapped rain water froze which caused the 2" pipe to rupture inside the comaprtment. This allowed product to leak out the drain pipe. All spilled product was contained within the load rack and went to an oil water separator.
column169: We introduce new procedures for checking/cleaning these drain tubes during regular trailer maintenance.

column168: At 08:5AM on 2-8-08, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised the following. Huntsville Fire Department personnel reported an odor emitting from an unknown train located at Old Phelps Road, Milepost 2.2 of the Huntsville Industrial Lead, in Huntsville, TX. Huntsville Fire personnel advised they were on scene with no further information available. Local  traffic was halted, and detoured around the area.    At 09:01AM, the train was identified as the MHOSH 08 which was stopped at this  location. Approximately 5 cars from the rear of the train, tank car UTLX 78762 was identified and alleged to be releasing a white cloud. Check of waybill information indicated car to be loaded with Corrosive Liquids, Toxic, N.O.S., Class 8, (6.1), UN2922, Sodium Hydrosulfide. Upon identifying the car, Mgr. Lerch requested the RMCC make shipper contact via Chem-Trec.    On arrival of  railroad personnel, Don Jenks, Manager of Environmental Field Operations confirmed there were no evacuations, injuries or exposures. Mgr. Jenks further stated there was no white cloud, and it appeared the cause of the odor was due to a failed manway gasket. On arrival, Mgr. Lerch inspected car UTLX 787862 noting a slight chemical odor in the air,and the the composition manway gasket to be wom and in poor condition. Additionally, there was approximately 1 gallon of dried product on the sides of the car. At 12:20PM, upon securing the car with a new manway nozzle gasket, the car was moved onto the Phelps siding track for deaning.    Mgr. Lerch  contacted shipper representatives from Lubrizol, and spoke to Greg Peran and Gary Fridge. Mgr. Lerch advised them the source of the release, corrective actions taken and that the exterior of the car would have to be cleaned. Arrangements were made by Lubrizol to have Garner Environmental respond and clean the car.    On 2-16-08 car UTLX 787862 was released for transportation in a secure, clean condition, and allowed to continue onto destination without further incident. There were no drains, waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this incident.
column169: PROPER PRE AND POST INSPECTIONS OF THE CAR PRIOR TO RELEASING FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: UPRR s Response Management Communications Center notified Lane A. Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials of a tank car suspected to be releasing material in track 21 of the Hoffman Yard in South St. Paul, MN. Mike Swentik, MYO, advised SHPX 203026, a load of hydrochloric acid, was reported to be venting from the top of the tank car when the car was moved. Mr. Sekavec requested that the car be isolated and to remain stationary.  Mr. Sekavec requested Hulcher Services (Contractor) respond and inspect the  tank car. Mr. Sekavec also made contact with Roger Bunting of Canexus Chemicals Canada (Shipper) to make them aware ot the incident and obtain any pertinent chemical information.  After making an inspection of the tank car, John Goelz, Project Manager for  Hulcher, advised that the riser for the air inlet piping was missing three of four nuts/bolts, allowing approximately sixteen ounces of product to be released on to the top of the tank car. Mr. Goelz replaced the nuts and bolts, resecuring the pipe riser. He also decontaminated the top of the tank car with a baking soda solution. No material reached the ground so no remediation was necessary. After completion of the work, the car was allowed to continue in transportation to the consignee.
column169: Ensure shippers inspect and maintain tank car piping.

column168: Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, reported a release of less than a pint of Potassium Hydroxide from Container SUDU 364199, due to a shifted load, onto cement within the ICTF Facility, Long Beach, CA. Mr. Cooper advised no waterways were effected, there were no exposures involved, and digging was not required. Mr. Cooper stated Transloading Environmental would remediate the concrete as well as around the outside the container and within the container. A single floor- loaded 275 gallon IBC tote had been punctured and damaged from a tote being placed on top of it. the top tote shifted in transit. The resulting puncture released an estimated 3 gallons of product. A second floor-loaded tote was also damaged from a tote being placed on top if it, however it did not leak. There was no bi-level separation between the floor loaded totes and the two top loaded second tier totes. The top tier totes slipped from their stacking configuration, damaging the cage on the bottom tier totes, resulting in impact and damage to the poly totes. The damaged tote product was transfered into a new tote and placed back into the original container with the remaining lading. The leaking tote product was transfered into a new tote, and is awaiting disposal per the shipper. Once reloaded and properly secured, the container was released for movement onto the consignee.
column169: PROPER BI-LEVEL SEPARATION

column168: On 02/28/2008 RMCC contacted Reg. Mgr M. Kelly and advised that tank car ECUX 374076 had been observed leaking in the Muskogee, OK yard.Upon inspection of the car it was found to have the bottom oulet valve handle unpinned and sightly open allowingproduct to drip from the bottom outlet cap that was less than tool tight.It was estimated that less than two gallons of product had beenreleased from the car.The bottom outlet valve was closed,the handle pinned and the bottom outlet cap was properly tightened.Thecar was then released to continue on to destination.
While unloading, unloader used a fitting with a check valve.  When the unloader opened the internal valve the check valve was open causing a two-gallon spill.
column169: We as a company train our drivers to included themselves in the unloading procedure as much as possible.  In doing so, our drivers are also trained to doubles check their connections and fittings to prevent instances like these.

column169: DO NOT STACK OTHER FREIGHT ON TOP OF PAINT. THE CANS ARE NOT STRONG ENOUGH TO SUPPORT ANY WEIGHT.

column168: Driver had hooked-up his product unload hose to customer storage tank fill connection and pressurized his load.  Walked to the back of trailer and opened trailer discharge valve.  Shortly thereafter, the driver saw product release into the air.  He was sprayed with product and assisted by plant personnel to the safety shower. Driver was not burned, however inhaled some of the fumes. He was treated and released at medical facility.  It was subsequently determined that a pipe nipple failed on the customer fill line releasing the product.  Plant personnel were able to shut off the valves.
column169: We worked with customer to 1) insure the piping was secure and adequate and inspected regularly, and 2)advised our drivers to do a thorough visual inspection of customer unload lines and if in doubt as to integrity, not to unload but notify dispatch.
